---
import PageLayout from '../../layouts/PageLayout.astro';
import CoastFireNumber from '../../components/calculator/CoastFireNumber.astro';
import StructuredData from '../../components/seo/StructuredData.astro';
import HowItWorks from '../../components/ui/HowItWorks.astro';
---

<PageLayout
  title="Coast FIRE Number Calculator — Find Your Coast FIRE Number by Age"
  description="Free Coast FIRE number calculator by age. Find out how much to coast FIRE at 35, 40, or any age, then let compound interest grow your savings to retirement."
  canonical="https://truefinancetools.com/coast-fire-number"
  ogImage="https://truefinancetools.com/og-coast-fire-number.png"
  ogImageAlt="Coast FIRE Number Calculator — Find Your Coast FIRE Number by Age"
  pageType="article"
  keywords="coast fire number, coast fire calculator by age, how much to coast fire at 35, coast fire number calculator, coast fire formula, compound interest retirement"
>
    <StructuredData
      title="Coast FIRE Number Calculator"
      description="Free Coast FIRE number calculator by age for estimating how much to save today so compound interest alone reaches your retirement target."
      url="https://truefinancetools.com/coast-fire-number"
      toolName="Coast FIRE Calculator"
      toolDescription="Calculate your Coast FIRE number — the amount you need today so compound interest alone reaches your full retirement target."
    />

    <CoastFireNumber />

    <HowItWorks title="How the Coast FIRE Number Calculator Works">
      <div class="text-center">
        <div class="mx-auto mb-4 flex h-12 w-12 items-center justify-center rounded-full bg-canvas-soft-2 text-ink">
          <svg class="h-6 w-6" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
            <path d="M12 6v12m-3-2.818l.879.659c1.171.879 3.07.879 4.242 0 1.172-.879 1.172-2.303 0-3.182C13.536 12.219 12.768 12 12 12c-.725 0-1.45-.22-2.003-.659-1.106-.879-1.106-2.303 0-3.182s2.9-.879 4.006 0l.415.33M21 12a9 9 0 11-18 0 9 9 0 0118 0z" />
          </svg>
        </div>
        <h3 class="mb-2 text-sm font-semibold text-ink">1. Enter Your Age and Retirement Target</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-body">Tell the calculator your current age and retirement age so it can estimate how many years your savings have to compound.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="text-center">
        <div class="mx-auto mb-4 flex h-12 w-12 items-center justify-center rounded-full bg-canvas-soft-2 text-ink">
          <svg class="h-6 w-6" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
            <path d="M12 6a6 6 0 100 12 6 6 0 000-12Zm0 8a2 2 0 100-4 2 2 0 000 4Z" />
          </svg>
        </div>
        <h3 class="mb-2 text-sm font-semibold text-ink">2. Add Expenses and Savings</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-body">Use your annual retirement expenses, current invested assets, expected return, inflation, and withdrawal assumptions.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="text-center">
        <div class="mx-auto mb-4 flex h-12 w-12 items-center justify-center rounded-full bg-canvas-soft-2 text-ink">
          <svg class="h-6 w-6" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
            <path d="M4 19.5h16M6 16.5l4-4 3 3L20 5.5" />
          </svg>
        </div>
        <h3 class="mb-2 text-sm font-semibold text-ink">3. See Your Coast FIRE Number</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-body">The tool shows the lump sum you need today, your progress, and whether your current savings can coast to retirement.</p>
      </div>
    </HowItWorks>

    <section class="border-t border-hairline bg-canvas-soft py-16">
      <div class="mx-auto max-w-4xl px-4 sm:px-6">
        <h2 class="mb-8 text-center text-2xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-ink" style="letter-spacing: -0.02em;">
          What is a Coast FIRE Number?
        </h2>

        <div class="prose prose-gray max-w-none text-body">
          <p class="mb-4">
            Your <strong>Coast FIRE number</strong> is the amount of money you need saved today so that compound interest alone — with zero additional contributions — will grow your portfolio to your full FIRE number by your target retirement age.
          </p>

          <p class="mb-4">
            Once you hit your Coast FIRE number, you no longer need to save aggressively. You only need to earn enough to cover your current living expenses. Your investments do the rest.
          </p>

          <h3 class="mb-3 text-lg font-semibold text-ink">The Coast FIRE Formula</h3>
          <div class="rounded-lg bg-canvas-soft-2 p-4 font-mono text-sm text-ink">
            Coast FIRE Number = (Annual Expenses × 25) / (1 + Return Rate)<sup>Years to Retirement</sup>
          </div>

          <p class="mb-4">
            For example, if you spend $60,000/year, your FIRE number is $1,500,000 (25× expenses). If you're 30, plan to retire at 55, and earn 7% annually: $1,500,000 / (1.07)<sup>25</sup> = <strong>$276,000</strong>. Once you save $276,000, you've "coasted" — compound interest will grow it to $1.5M by age 55.
          </p>

          <h3 class="mb-3 text-lg font-semibold text-ink">Coast FIRE by Age</h3>
          <div class="grid gap-4 sm:grid-cols-2">
            <div class="rounded-lg border border-hairline bg-canvas p-4">
              <h4 class="mb-2 text-sm font-semibold text-link">At 25 (30 years to retirement)</h4>
              <p class="text-sm text-body">You need roughly 20% of your FIRE number saved. With 7% returns, $150K saved grows to ~$1.14M by 55.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="rounded-lg border border-hairline bg-canvas p-4">
              <h4 class="mb-2 text-sm font-semibold text-link">At 30 (25 years to retirement)</h4>
              <p class="text-sm text-body">You need roughly 18% of your FIRE number saved. $150K grows to ~$815K by 55 at 7% returns.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="rounded-lg border border-hairline bg-canvas p-4">
              <h4 class="mb-2 text-sm font-semibold text-link">At 35 (20 years to retirement)</h4>
              <p class="text-sm text-body">You need roughly 26% of your FIRE number saved. $150K grows to ~$580K by 55 at 7% returns.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="rounded-lg border border-hairline bg-canvas p-4">
              <h4 class="mb-2 text-sm font-semibold text-link">At 40 (15 years to retirement)</h4>
              <p class="text-sm text-body">You need roughly 36% of your FIRE number saved. $150K grows to ~$414K by 55 at 7% returns.</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <h3 class="mb-3 mt-8 text-lg font-semibold text-ink">Who Should Use This Calculator?</h3>
          <div class="grid gap-4 sm:grid-cols-2">
            <div class="rounded-lg border border-hairline bg-canvas p-4">
              <h4 class="mb-2 text-sm font-semibold text-ink">Career Changers</h4>
              <p class="text-sm text-body">Switch to lower-paying but fulfilling work once you've coasted. Your savings grow while you enjoy the journey.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="rounded-lg border border-hairline bg-canvas p-4">
              <h4 class="mb-2 text-sm font-semibold text-ink">Semi-Retirees</h4>
              <p class="text-sm text-body">Reduce to part-time work. Let compound interest cover the gap between part-time income and full retirement.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="rounded-lg border border-hairline bg-canvas p-4">
              <h4 class="mb-2 text-sm font-semibold text-ink">Young Savers</h4>
              <p class="text-sm text-body">In your 20s or 30s? Time is your biggest asset. Calculate your Coast FIRE number and see how early you can relax.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="rounded-lg border border-hairline bg-canvas p-4">
              <h4 class="mb-2 text-sm font-semibold text-ink">Parents</h4>
              <p class="text-sm text-body">Want to be present for your kids' childhood? Coast FIRE lets you step back from full-time work without derailing retirement.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="border-t border-hairline bg-canvas py-16">
      <div class="mx-auto max-w-4xl px-4 sm:px-6">
        <h2 class="mb-8 text-center text-2xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-ink" style="letter-spacing: -0.02em;">
          Frequently Asked Questions About Coast FIRE Numbers
        </h2>

        <div class="space-y-4">
          <details class="group rounded-lg border border-hairline bg-canvas p-4 shadow-sm">
            <summary class="cursor-pointer py-2 text-sm font-medium text-ink">What is a Coast FIRE number calculator?</summary>
            <p class="mt-3 text-sm text-body">A <strong>Coast FIRE number calculator</strong> estimates how much you need invested today so your portfolio can grow to your retirement target without future contributions. It combines your age, retirement age, annual expenses, withdrawal multiplier, expected return, and inflation to calculate your Coast FIRE target.</p>
          </details>

          <details class="group rounded-lg border border-hairline bg-canvas p-4 shadow-sm">
            <summary class="cursor-pointer py-2 text-sm font-medium text-ink">How does a Coast FIRE calculator by age work?</summary>
            <p class="mt-3 text-sm text-body">A <strong>Coast FIRE calculator by age</strong> uses the years between now and retirement as the compounding period. The earlier you start, the less you need today because your investments have more time to grow.</p>
          </details>

          <details class="group rounded-lg border border-hairline bg-canvas p-4 shadow-sm">
            <summary class="cursor-pointer py-2 text-sm font-medium text-ink">How much do I need to Coast FIRE at 35?</summary>
            <p class="mt-3 text-sm text-body">To answer <strong>how much to Coast FIRE at 35</strong>, estimate your retirement expenses, multiply them by your withdrawal multiplier, and discount that future FIRE number back to today. For example, $60,000 in annual expenses, a 25x multiplier, 30 years to age 65, and 7% annual returns means a Coast FIRE number of about $196,000.</p>
          </details>

          <details class="group rounded-lg border border-hairline bg-canvas p-4 shadow-sm">
            <summary class="cursor-pointer py-2 text-sm font-medium text-ink">Is Coast FIRE the same as full FIRE?</summary>
            <p class="mt-3 text-sm text-body">No. Full FIRE means your portfolio can cover your retirement expenses without employment income. Coast FIRE means your current portfolio can grow to your future FIRE number, but you still need to cover today's living expenses until retirement.</p>
          </details>

          <details class="group rounded-lg border border-hairline bg-canvas p-4 shadow-sm">
            <summary class="cursor-pointer py-2 text-sm font-medium text-ink">Should monthly contributions be included?</summary>
            <p class="mt-3 text-sm text-body">Set monthly contributions to $0 to see your pure Coast FIRE number. Add contributions if you want to model how extra savings can help you reach the target sooner.</p>
          </details>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="border-t border-hairline bg-canvas-soft py-16">
      <div class="mx-auto max-w-4xl px-4 sm:px-6">
        <h2 class="mb-6 text-2xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-ink" style="letter-spacing: -0.02em;">
          Complete Guide to Using a Coast FIRE Number Calculator
        </h2>

        <div class="prose prose-gray max-w-none text-body">
          <p class="mb-4">
            A <strong>coast fire number calculator</strong> is designed for one specific question: how much money do you need invested today so you can stop making retirement contributions and still reach your target by retirement age? This is different from a standard FIRE calculator, which usually projects how long it will take to build your full retirement portfolio. Coast FIRE focuses on the starting point where your current investments can do the rest of the work through compound growth.
          </p>

          <p class="mb-4">
            The key advantage of using a <strong>Coast FIRE calculator by age</strong> is that it makes time visible. A 25-year-old may need a relatively small percentage of their future FIRE number because decades of growth remain. A 45-year-old may need a much larger lump sum because the compounding window is shorter. By entering your current age and retirement age, you can see how each year changes the target.
          </p>

          <p class="mb-4">
            For anyone searching <strong>how much to Coast FIRE at 35</strong>, the answer depends on your expenses, expected return, inflation, and retirement age. The calculator helps you test those assumptions instantly. Increase your annual return, lower your retirement expenses, or push retirement later, and your Coast FIRE number will adjust in real time.
          </p>

          <p class="mb-4">
            The formula is simple, but the planning impact is powerful: calculate your future FIRE number, then discount it back to today using your expected annual return and years to retirement. Once your invested assets reach that Coast FIRE number, your investment account should theoretically grow to your retirement target without additional contributions, assuming your return assumptions hold.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="border-t border-hairline bg-canvas py-16">
      <div class="mx-auto max-w-4xl px-4 text-center sm:px-6">
        <h2 class="mb-4 text-2xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-ink" style="letter-spacing: -0.02em;">
          Explore Other FIRE Strategies
        </h2>
        <p class="mb-8 text-body">Compare different approaches to find the right one for your lifestyle.</p>

        <div class="grid gap-4 sm:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-3">
          <a href="/lean-fire-calculator" class="group rounded-lg border border-hairline bg-canvas p-5 text-left shadow-sm transition-all hover:shadow-md">
            <h3 class="mb-2 text-sm font-semibold text-ink group-hover:text-link">Lean FIRE Calculator</h3>
            <p class="text-xs text-body">Minimalist approach with lower expenses.</p>
          </a>
          <a href="/fat-fire-calculator" class="group rounded-lg border border-hairline bg-canvas p-5 text-left shadow-sm transition-all hover:shadow-md">
            <h3 class="mb-2 text-sm font-semibold text-ink group-hover:text-link">Fat FIRE Calculator</h3>
            <p class="text-xs text-body">For those who want a luxury retirement lifestyle.</p>
          </a>
          <a href="/barista-fire-calculator" class="group rounded-lg border border-hairline bg-canvas p-5 text-left shadow-sm transition-all hover:shadow-md">
            <h3 class="mb-2 text-sm font-semibold text-ink group-hover:text-link">Barista FIRE Calculator</h3>
            <p class="text-xs text-body">Work part-time, let investments cover the rest.</p>
          </a>
          <a href="/fire-calculator" class="group rounded-lg border border-hairline bg-canvas p-5 text-left shadow-sm transition-all hover:shadow-md">
            <h3 class="mb-2 text-sm font-semibold text-ink group-hover:text-link">FIRE Calculator</h3>
            <p class="text-xs text-body">Compare all FIRE strategies side by side.</p>
          </a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>
</PageLayout>
